          "evidence_text_excerpt": "What is the difference between a traditional savings account and a high-interest savings account?\nThe main difference between a traditional savings account and a high-interest savings account is the interest rates. Even with a small initial deposit in a HISA, its more favourable rates, along with the power of compound interest, can accelerate the growth of your money.\nLet's break it down with an example: Imagine you want to deposit $20,000 into a savings account. Your traditional\u00a0 savings account might give you a 0.10% interest rate, but a HISA could offer a much more appealing 1.35% interest rate annually. If you stick with your regular account, after a year, you'll have $20,040 to your name. But if you go for the HISA and make no transactions that incur fees, you\u2019ll see $20,271.68 in your account after the first year, earning an extra $230 in interest just by choosing a different type",
