          "evidence_text_excerpt": "Limitations of a high-interest savings account\nWhen considering a high-interest savings account (HISA), it\u2019s important to weigh both the pros and cons. Some drawbacks to be aware of include:\nWithdrawal limits: You may be limited to a certain number of transactions included in each billing cycle, beyond which you\u2019ll be charged for each additional transaction. Your HISA may not limit how much you can transfer or withdraw, but it may still cap how many times it can be done per cycle.\nWithdrawal limits:\nFluctuating rates: Even if you open a HISA at an attractive promotional interest rate, there\u2019s no guarantee it will stay there. Interest rates on HISAs are variable and can change at any time.\nFluctuating rates:\nLimited growth: Compared with traditional savings accounts, a HISA will certainly earn more. But those earnings can\u2019t compete with investment options. A TFSA , for example, or",
